589
63:50.880 --> 63:56.790
It's a truly fascinating algorithm, and if you're interested in it, you should definitely check it out.

590
63:56.790 --> 64:02.460
It's very closely connected to Euclid's algorithm for
computing GCDs in fact.

591
64:02.460 --> 64:06.570
But I won't say anything
more about it in this video.

592
64:06.570 --> 64:13.500
The point of this is that if we have a good
approximation to some fraction for which the numerator and
denominator aren't too big,

593
64:13.500 --> 64:17.880
the algorithm can recover the fraction, and that's what we're doing here.

594
64:17.880 --> 64:24.720
And now we're left with exactly
the same question as before, which is how much precision do we need?

595
64:24.720 --> 64:30.000
And it turns out that
exactly the same bound that we had before works in this case.

596
64:30.000 --> 64:37.440
And so choosing M in exactly
the same way as before works here as well.

597
64:37.440 --> 64:40.680
Now this isn't necessarily
going to tell us R.

598
64:40.680 --> 64:47.580
What we'll learn if we use
enough precision, is J over R, but that will be a
fraction in lowest terms.

599
64:47.580 --> 64:53.640
So we could get unlucky in the sense that this random choice of J could have common factors with R,

600
64:53.640 --> 65:01.020
and they'll be hidden from us. In the worst case for instance, we could get J equals zero and we will learn absolutely nothing.

601
65:01.020 --> 65:04.650
But that is literally the only
case where we learn nothing.

602
65:04.650 --> 65:11.550
In general, we'll at least
get a non-trivial factor of R, and if we're able to draw random samples

603
65:11.550 --> 65:18.750
and get psi J for different choices of J, we can in fact recover
R with high probability by computing the least common multiple

604
65:18.750 --> 65:25.320
of all of the denominators
that we observe. And this actually doesn't
require very many samples at all.

605
65:25.320 --> 65:31.740
The bottom line is that some choices of J will hide factors of R, but random choices of J

606
65:31.740 --> 65:35.460
won't be able to hide the
factors of R for long.

607
65:35.460 --> 65:45.240
So that is the idea. It remains to consider the implementation and in particular to figure
out how much it costs.

608
65:45.240 --> 65:52.560
The essence of the idea, to compute the order of a
given element A and ZN star is to apply the phase estimation procedure

609
65:52.560 --> 65:56.430
to the operation MA.

610
65:56.430 --> 66:03.840
Let's figure out what
the cost of doing this is as a function of the length of capital N, which I'll denote by little n.

611
66:03.840 --> 66:09.840
Here's a circuit for phase estimation. We're going to need little n qubits on the bottom part of the circuit

612
66:09.840 --> 66:17.190
to encode elements of ZN in binary. So we have N control qubits on top and little n qubits on the bottom,

613
66:17.190 --> 66:23.370
which is nice because that matches with the names that we
used earlier in the lesson.

614
66:23.370 --> 66:31.680
In order to count the
number of gates that we need for the entire circuit, let's focus first on the cost of the controlled unitary operations.

615
66:31.680 --> 66:39.780
If we use the techniques
from the previous lesson, lesson six, we can implement MA using big O of little n squared gates

616
66:39.780 --> 66:44.727
using efficient classical algorithms for arithmetic modular N.

617
66:44.727 --> 66:53.760
I'll skip the details in this video, but like several other
things I've talked about, you can read more about it in the written material for the lesson.

618
66:53.760 --> 66:57.000
It's not enough though
to implement just MA.

619
66:57.000 --> 67:03.330
We also need to implement MA squared, MA to the fourth power, to
the eighth power, and so on

620
67:03.330 --> 67:08.400
all the way up to MA to a power that's exponential in M.

621
67:08.400 --> 67:14.100
And we know we're going to need to take M to be linear in little n
to get enough precision.

622
67:14.100 --> 67:17.850
This is a big concern,
and I raised it earlier.

623
67:17.850 --> 67:28.080
If we were to implement powers
of MA by simply iterating MA, we'd be in trouble because all these iterations of MA
would incur exponential cost.

624
67:28.080 --> 67:33.270
Fortunately, we can play a trick to avoid this blow up in cost.

625
67:33.270 --> 67:38.490
What we can do is as follows, for each power K that we need.

626
67:38.490 --> 67:42.930
First, we compute A to
the power K, modular N.

627
67:42.930 --> 67:47.130
This is the modular exponentiation problem that I mentioned in lesson six.

628
67:47.130 --> 67:51.660
And it can be solved efficiently. And this is something that we can do with a classical computer.

629
67:51.660 --> 67:55.950
This computation doesn't
need to be performed by a quantum circuit at all.

630
67:55.950 --> 67:59.070
So let's let B be the result.

631
67:59.070 --> 68:03.060
So B is an element of ZN star.

632
68:03.060 --> 68:09.450
And second, in place of MA to the power K, we just use a circuit for MB.

633
68:09.450 --> 68:18.690
And that's it. B is just some element of ZN star, So the cost to implement MB
is big O of little n squared.

634
68:18.690 --> 68:25.770
In a nutshell, what we're doing is exponentating in ZN rather than exponentating
a quantum circuit.

635
68:25.770 --> 68:31.590
But the actual operation we
get is the same either way. It's just multiplication by A, K times.

636
68:31.590 --> 68:38.790
This is kind of a miracle in fact. And we wouldn't be able to
solve the order finding problem or effect integers efficiently
with a quantum computer

637
68:38.790 --> 68:42.450
if it wasn't for this.

638
68:42.450 --> 68:48.655
And now that we know that each of the controlled
unitary operations, including the powers, can be implemented

639
68:48.655 --> 68:53.520
at cost big O events squared, we can count the total
number of gates we need.

640
68:53.520 --> 69:01.260
We have N Hadamard gates, and because M is equal
to big O of little n, the cost is big O of little n.

